  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2015340031" />
    <a title="Halima" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63550047-halima"><img alt="Halima" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1601035795p2/63550047.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2015340031?book_show_action=true">May 31, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Halima" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Halima" href="/user/show/63550047-halima">Halima</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/63550047-halima?shelf=%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%8A%D8%A9">عربية</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2015340031" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8592349722706748218">Overall, the book is okay-ish for self-improvement and all but I had some issues with it.<br/><br/>It&apos;s a good reminder for many people. For me as well. That life is hard but if we come across so and so obstacle it is for a reason or another and all the blah blah of self-help and stuff. That being said, we hear the same exact things over and over and over again on a daily basis. They&apos;re more cliché than the bad-boy-and-the-innocent-girl cliché. And God! How I hate the latter. I personally I&apos;m tired of the</span>
  <span id="freeText8592349722706748218" style="display:none">Overall, the book is okay-ish for self-improvement and all but I had some issues with it.<br /><br />It's a good reminder for many people. For me as well. That life is hard but if we come across so and so obstacle it is for a reason or another and all the blah blah of self-help and stuff. That being said, we hear the same exact things over and over and over again on a daily basis. They're more cliché than the bad-boy-and-the-innocent-girl cliché. And God! How I hate the latter. I personally I'm tired of these sayings. And I'm only pointing it <i>this</i> much because it is so hyped that I thought it'd be something new. Something that would help me more than what's in the book.<br /><br />It was also very repetitive. Same things said over and over again in many chapters. Sometimes in different ways; not my cup of tea.<br /><br />All in all. It is a good reminder, it also gives some strong examples from our religion and that's lovely, I think.<br /><br />I recommend reading when you feel down or if you just want to feel better. It's not going to be a magical trick and you'll be able to challenge your boss by yourself just like that, but sometimes we need to hear the words that we all but fully know by heart just to regain consciousness of ourselves and lives.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8592349722706748218" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


